  "prompt": "Which is the greatest theft that has happened in the history of the world?",
  "response": "Determining the \"greatest theft\" in history can depend on various criteria, including the value of the stolen items, cultural significance, or the notoriety of the crime. Here are a few notable incidents often cited:\n\n1. **Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum Heist (1990)**: In this infamous case, two men disguised as police officers gained entry to the museum in Boston and stole 13 pieces of art valued at around $500 million. The artwork has never been recovered, making it one of the most significant art thefts in history.\n\n2. **Theft of the Gold Train (1945)**: At the end of World War II, a train carrying gold, jewels, and other valuables looted by the Nazis reportedly went missing in Germany. The value of the stolen items remains uncertain, but estimates suggest it could be worth billions today.\n\n3. **The Great Train Robbery (1963)**: A gang in the UK managed to steal \u00a32.6 million (around \u00a350 million today) from a Royal Mail train by staging a fake signalman and stopping the train. The heist is famous and involved meticulous planning.\n\n4. **Theft of the Diamond Necklace (1785)**: This theft of a diamond necklace from the French crown jewels, which involved complex deception and scandal, is often associated with the downfall of Marie Antoinette and contributed to the French Revolution.\n\n5. **The Great British Looter (2006)**: This involved the theft of jewelry worth roughly \u00a350 million from a safe deposit box company in London, showcasing a sophisticated and well-planned burglary.\n\nThe definition of \"greatest\" can vary, so while these examples highlight significant thefts, opinions may differ based on how one measures \"greatness.\"",
